e new scanners only for different types (ex: strings) of inputs. \n\nSo instead of 2 scanners you need two ints and one scanner.\n\n    Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);\n    System.out.println(\"enter number1: \");\n\t int num1 = input.nextInt();\n    System.out.println(\"enter number2: \");\n    int num2 = input.nextInt();\n    int numSum = num1 + num2;\n\n<rant>\n\nThis is why I hate when they teach Java as a beginner language. What sense is a beginner going to make out of that crap. And this method is incredibly wrongly named. I can see why you would think all the ints are already in there and you're just taking the next one when the method is named like that.\n\n</rant>", "id": "e5c05s1", "replies": [{"body": "I would only create a new scanner object if I was going to get input from a different stream such as a file as opposed to the keyboard.  \n\nYou can use next(), nextInt(), nextDouble() interchangeably with the same Scanner object. Just be careful when mixing nextLine() with the other next... methods.   ", "id": "e5c0y92", "replies": []}]}, {"body": "Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);   // you should use one object of Scanner class, then you can use it multiple times to assign values to variables\n\nSystem.out.println(\"enter number1: \");\n\nint num1 = input.nextInt();\n\nSystem.out.println(\"enter number2: \");\n\nint num2 = input.nextInt();\n\nint numSum = num1+ num2;\n\nSystem.out.println(\"sum: \" + numSum);", "id": "e5c06zy", "replies": []}], "title": "[Java] How to not print all the print statements after running code when dealing with user input?"}